</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td><strong>Iran</strong></td>
<td>Islamic Republic under Shiite Shari'a law</td>
<td>Civil, penal, financial, administrative, military and other public laws must conform to Islam</td>
<td>Const. Iran 1979 (rev. 2002)</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td><strong>Iraq</strong></td>
<td>Shia are majority; Sunni apply many schools</td>
<td><p>Const. Article (2): 1st - Islam is the official religion of the state and is a basic source of legislation:</p>
<p>(a) No law can be passed that contradicts the undisputed rules of Islam.</p></td>
<td><a href="https://www.constituteproject.org/constitution/Iraq_2005?lang=en">Const. Iraq 2005</a></td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td><strong>Israel</strong></td>
<td>Jewish law, Islamic law, Canon law for each community</td>
<td>Personal status and family law</td>
<td>Religious courts for each community or sect, such as Druze, and in many areas applies if both parties are of same religious group, mixed with secular law; <a href="https://www.constituteproject.org/constitution/Israel_2013?lang=en">Const. 1958 (rev. 2013)</a></td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td><strong>Jordan</strong></td>
<td>Islamic law</td>
<td>Mixed laws</td>
